nerve (V)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sphenoid bone is a complex bone located at the base of the skull, and it plays a role in the passage of several cranial nerves. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve (II)\u003C/strong\u003E passes through the optic canal, which is part of the sphenoid bone. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve (III)\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve (IV)\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal nerve (V)\u003C/strong\u003E all pass through the superior orbital fissure, which is also part of the sphenoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eolfactory nerve (I)\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with the sphenoid bone. Instead, it passes through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone, which is located anteriorly in the skull. Therefore, the sphenoid bone does not have a role with the olfactory nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sphenoid bone is associated with several cranial nerves, including the optic nerve (II), oculomotor nerve (III), trochlear nerve (IV), and trigeminal nerve (V).","The olfactory nerve (I) is not associated with the sphenoid bone, as it passes through the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":